Exercise 2 (8pts)

These are warmups for the later questions. We will work through the examples in the lecture notes, and make sure that they all work for you, and that you know what each function does.

  1. (3pts) Tidy the genes data.
    1. Which function makes the long tidy form? gather
    2. Which function separates the text strings into two variables? separate
    3. What two functions create new text values that have no leading W? mutate, sub
library(tidyverse)
genes <- read_csv("genes.csv")
gtidy <- genes %>%
  gather(variable, expr, -id) %>%
  separate(variable, c("trt", "leftover"), "-") %>%
  separate(leftover, c("time", "rep"), "\\.") %>%
  mutate(trt = sub("W", "", trt)) %>%
  mutate(rep = sub("R", "", rep))
  1. (5pts) Tidy the Melbourne weather station data.
    1. What does the function read.fwf do? What does the argument c(11, 4, 2, 4, rep(c(5, 1, 1, 1), 31)) do in the function? Sets the number of columns corresponding to each value
    2. What is the difference between [] and ()? What does [,c(1,2,3,4,seq(5,128,4))] do in the second line? [] is used for indexing matrices and vectors, () is used with functions for providing input parameters
    3. Which function removes records other than the temperature and precipitation? filter
    4. What does the spread function do here? puts TMIN, TMX, PRCP into separate columns
    5. Why do the raw temperature and precipitation values get divided by 10? The original value was given without a decimal point
melbtemp <- read.fwf("ASN00086282.dly", 
                     c(11, 4, 2, 4, rep(c(5, 1, 1, 1), 31)), fill=T)
melbtemp <- melbtemp[,c(1,2,3,4,seq(5,128,4))]
colnames(melbtemp) <- c("id", "year", "month", "var", paste0("V",1:31))
melbtemp <- melbtemp %>% 
  gather(day, value, V1:V31) %>%
  mutate(day = sub("V", "", day)) %>%
  mutate(value=ifelse(value==-9999, NA, value)) %>%
  filter(var %in% c("PRCP", "TMAX", "TMIN")) %>%
  spread(var, value) %>%
  mutate(PRCP=PRCP/10, TMAX=TMAX/10, TMIN=TMIN/10)

Exercise 3 (2pts)

41% Of Fliers Think Youre Rude If You Recline Your Seat. In the following table, V1 is a response to the question Is it rude to recline your seat on a plane?, and V2 is the response to the question Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?.

fly <- read_csv("flying-etiquette.csv")
glimpse(fly)
fly_tbl <- fly %>% 
  filter(`Is itrude to recline your seat on a plane?` %in% 
           c("No, not rude at all", "Yes, somewhat rude", "Yes, very rude")) %>%
  filter(`Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?` %in%
           c("Always","Usually", "About half the time","Once in a while", "Never")) %>%
  mutate(`Is itrude to recline your seat on a plane?` =
           factor(`Is itrude to recline your seat on a plane?`, 
    levels=c("No, not rude at all", "Yes, somewhat rude",
             "Yes, very rude")), 
`Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?` = 
  factor(`Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?`,
         levels=c("Always","Usually", "About half the time",
                  "Once in a while", "Never"))) %>%
  group_by(`Is itrude to recline your seat on a plane?`, `Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?`) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(`Do you ever recline your seat when you fly?`, n)
write_csv(fly_tbl, path="fly_tbl.csv")
fly_tbl <- read_csv("fly_tbl.csv")
library(knitr)

Exercise 5 (5pts)

Read in the billboard top 100 music data, which contains NSync and Backstreet Boys songs that entered the billboard charts in the year 2000.

billboard <- read_csv("billboard.csv")
  1. Whats in this data? Whats 1-76? What are the variables? Each line corresponds to one song. And the columns correspond to weeks, with 76 being the longest number of weeks a song stayed in the top 100. None of these songs were there that long.
  2. Convert this data into a long format appropriate for plotting a time series (date on the x axis, chart position on the y axis) See code below
  3. Make a time series plot, where each song is its own line, and the line is coloured by the artist. It should look like this. Which song was the most successful? What song was the least successful? (Explain your reasoning, or metrics, for saying a song is more or less successful.) See code below. Most successful song, based on weeks on the charts, was N'Sync This I promise you. Least successful song was Backstreet Boys The One, which peaked quickly and tanked fast.
long_billboard <- billboard %>% 
  gather(key = week, value = rank, `1`:`76`) %>%
  mutate(week = as.numeric(week), rank=as.numeric(rank)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(rank))

ggplot(data = long_billboard, 
       aes(x=week, y=rank, colour = artist, group = track)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")

whalesharks <- read_csv("whaleshark-encounters.csv")
  1. Is a whale shark, a whale? No
  2. What are the observations is this data? Each encounter with a whale shark.
  3. What info potentially is replicated on multiple lines? That is, the records are an example of repeated measurements, sometimes called longitudinal or panel data. Whale sharks are seen repeatedly, and the same observers report multiple whale sharks.
